  <!-- ================= BUSINESS ================= -->
  <section>
    <h2><span class="n">3.</span>Business Overview</h2>
    <p>Incorporated in <strong>2001</strong> by founder &amp; Managing Director <strong>Narendra Narayanan</strong> (USC electrical engineer; son Sumukh Narendra is Executive Director), Vinyas listed on the <strong>NSE Emerge (SME) platform in October 2023</strong> and operates a single &gt;150,000 sq ft facility in Mysuru, including a dedicated export (EHTP) unit and a high-reliability Class-III defence line.</p>
    <h3>What it does</h3>
    <p>Vinyas is a pure-play EMS/ODM provider deliberately focused on <strong>high-complexity, low-to-medium-volume</strong> work, which carries higher entry barriers and steadier margins than commodity consumer EMS:</p>
    <span class="chip">PCB assembly / SMT &amp; THT</span><span class="chip">Box build &amp; system integration</span><span class="chip">Cable &amp; wire harnessing</span><span class="chip">Design / DFM &amp; NPI</span><span class="chip">Testing &amp; inspection (ESS/HASS)</span><span class="chip">Aftermarket / repair</span>
    <h3>End-markets &amp; mix</h3>
    <p>Six verticals — Aerospace &amp; Defence, Medical, Automotive, Industrial, Telecom and Consumer — but the business is heavily skewed: <strong>defence &amp; aerospace is ~85–90% of the order book</strong> (~78% of H1-FY26 revenue). <strong>Exports are ~50% of revenue</strong> (Europe and the US), which usefully diversifies away from pure Indian-PSU dependence.</p>
    <h3>Credentials &amp; customers</h3>
    <p>The moat in defence EMS is qualification, not price. Vinyas holds <strong>AS9100-D</strong> (aerospace QMS — the gatekeeper credential), a <strong>Defence Industrial Licence</strong>, <strong>ISO 13485</strong> (medical), and received <strong>NADCAP</strong> accreditation in 2025. <strong>Bharat Electronics (BEL)</strong> is a confirmed recurring customer (orders of ₹43.5 cr and ₹26.25 cr documented); exact customer concentration is not disclosed, and the IPO prospectus flagged reliance on a single large customer — a risk to monitor.</p>
    <h3>Recent strategic moves</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>US subsidiary</strong> — Vinyas Innovative Technologies Inc., wholly-owned, incorporated May 2026, to build US business-development presence.</li>
      <li><strong>Israel defence JV</strong> — 26% Vinyas / 74% Israeli partner (₹2.6 cr investment, May 2026) for manufacturing, integration and lifecycle support; ~10–15% of supplies are already Israel-sourced.</li>
      <li><strong>Capacity expansion</strong> — new SMT lines and quality upgrades; ~₹30 cr FY26 capex against just 35–40% utilisation.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= INDUSTRY ================= -->
  <section>
    <h2><span class="n">4.</span>Industry &amp; Structural Opportunity</h2>
    <p>Vinyas sits at the intersection of two strong, policy-backed tailwinds:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian EMS</strong> — variously sized at US$35–65 bn (2025) growing ~10–18% CAGR; brokerages model the <em>listed</em> EMS universe at ~30% revenue CAGR over FY25–28. A ₹22,919 cr electronics-component PLI (approved 2025), "Make in India", import substitution and China+1 underpin demand.</li>
      <li><strong>Defence indigenisation</strong> — India's defence production has crossed ~US$18 bn; five Positive Indigenisation Lists earmark 5,000+ items for domestic manufacture, with a target to raise indigenous content past 70%. Defence electronics &amp; avionics is estimated to roughly double to ~US$17.6 bn by 2031.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For a small, defence-skewed contract manufacturer, this is a favourable backdrop: certified suppliers to defence primes enjoy sticky, multi-year, higher-margin programmes that larger consumer-EMS players underprioritise. The ~50% export tilt adds global-supply-chain optionality beyond domestic budgets. The flip side is that the thesis leans on policy continuity and is exposed to <strong>lumpy, milestone-driven revenue recognition</strong>, common across defence peers.</p>
  </section>

