      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>The balance sheet improved markedly: the FY24 equity raise de-levered D/E from 1.87× to 0.71×, and the ₹150 cr 2025 warrant issue lifted net worth further. Reported returns are healthy (ROE/ROCE in the mid-teens to high-teens). Leverage is no longer the worry — <strong>cash conversion is.</strong></p>

    <div class="box crux">
      <div class="bt">⚑ The crux — profits aren't becoming cash</div>
      As an EMS firm selling to slow-paying government/PSU and defence customers, Vinyas is structurally working-capital heavy — and the data shows it worsening, not improving. This is the single most important slide in the report.
    </div>

    <h3>Cash flow &amp; working capital (₹ cr / days, standalone)</h3>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>FY21</th><th>FY22</th><th>FY23</th><th>FY24</th><th>FY25</th><th>FY26</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Operating cash flow</td><td class="neg">-25</td><td class="pos">12</td><td class="pos">12</td><td class="neg">-29</td><td class="pos">9</td><td class="neg">-32</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Free cash flow (approx.)</td><td class="neg">-27</td><td class="pos">11</td><td class="pos">9</td><td class="neg">-57</td><td class="pos">7</td><td class="neg">-77</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Receivable days</td><td>52</td><td>100</td><td>33</td><td>101</td><td>163</td><td>161</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Inventory days</td><td>238</td><td>247</td><td>211</td><td>166</td><td>88</td><td>114</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Payable days</td><td>93</td><td>130</td><td>71</td><td>74</td><td>36</td><td>43</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cash conversion cycle</td><td>197</td><td>217</td><td>173</td><td>193</td><td>216</td><td><strong>232</strong></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Three things to absorb: (1) operating cash flow has been negative in three of the last six years, including FY26 despite record profit; (2) receivable days have <strong>doubled</strong> while payable days <strong>collapsed</strong> — a double squeeze (collecting slower, paying suppliers faster); (3) the cash conversion cycle is ~⅔ of a year and lengthening. The mechanical consequence is that growth must be financed externally — exactly what the rising working-capital debt and the warrant raise are doing. <strong>This is the metric to watch every results cycle.</strong></p>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= VALUATION ================= -->
  <section>
    <h2><span class="n">6.</span>Valuation</h2>
    <p>At ₹1,405, Vinyas trades at ~57–60× trailing earnings, ~8× book and ~32× EV/EBITDA — a full re-rating (the stock is up ~50% over 52 weeks and near its high). That sits within the listed defence-EMS cluster (peers at ~54–71× P/E) but offers <strong>limited margin of safety</strong> for a sub-₹520 cr-revenue company with negative free cash flow.</p>

